<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Alhambra_Decree#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFYanes" class="citation web">Yanes, Javier. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120721214231/http://www.publico.es/ciencias/180536/tres-culturas-en-el-adn">"Tres culturas en el ADN"</a> &#91;Three cultures in DNA&#93; (in Spanish). Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.publico.es/ciencias/180536/tres/culturas/adn">the original</a> on 21 July 2012<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">9 September</span> 2016</span>. <q>[English translation] The Sephardi result may be overestimated, since there is much diversity in those genes and maybe absorbed other genes from the Middle East. Puts Calafell in doubt the validity of ancestry tests? They can be good for the Americans, we already know from where we come from.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Tres+culturas+en+el+ADN&amp;rft.aulast=Yanes&amp;rft.aufirst=Javier&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.publico.es%2Fciencias%2F180536%2Ftres%2Fculturas%2Fadn&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAlhambra+Decree" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
